							<h3 class="invis">Author bio</h3>
																																															<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/devon-bidal/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_bottom" >
											<div class="container col3 ">
												<div class="col span2"><p>Devon Bidal is a British Columbia–based journalist and editor who focuses on archaeology, paleontology, culture, and climate. Her writing has been published in numerous outlets including <em>Smithsonian, Atlas Obscura, The Tyee, Popular Science, Cottage Life, </em>and more. When she’s not working, Devon can be found poking around tide pools, crocheting, cycling, and searching for the ultimate fish taco. Before joining the <em>Hakai Magazine</em> team full-time, she was a 2021 Tula Foundation Journalism Fellow and a Ma Murray New Journalist of the Year. Photo by Sam DeCosse</p></div>
												<div class="singlebioimage col nomobile"><img width="520" height="520" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/devon-bidal-520x520.jpg" class="attachment-medium size-medium wp-post-image" alt="Devon Bidal" decoding="async" loading="lazy" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/devon-bidal-520x520.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/devon-bidal-150x150.jpg 150w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/devon-bidal.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 520px) 100vw, 520px" /></div>
